Data analysis

Data source

I got my data by downloading the file of my artist, which was extracted using the spotifyr package, and then storing it in the data folder.

Import data

#packages needed for analysis
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

#importing data into df
df <- read.csv("Mimi Webb.csv")

Data preparation

# Remove records with the same track names
df <- df |> distinct(track_name, .keep_all = TRUE)
# Filter out track names that include "Live at" or "Live Acoustic"
df <- df |> filter(!grepl("Live at|Live Acoustic", track_name))
# Change the data type of album_name from numeric into character
df$album_name <- as.character(df$album_name)

Album analysis

# Change album_name from character to factor before starting the plot
df$album_name <- as.factor(df$album_name)
# Boxplot
ggplot(df, aes(x=album_name, y=loudness, color=album_name))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title= "Boxplots Albums", x="Album name", y="Loudness")

Seven Shades of Heartbreak is louder than Amelia!

Valence and Loudness of her songs

# Labeling songs
subgroup <- df |> filter(track_name %in% c("Halfway", "Ghost of You", "Little Bit Louder"))
# Scatterplot
p <- ggplot(df, aes(x=valence, y=loudness, color=album_name))+
      geom_point()+
      geom_hline(yintercept=-7, color="grey")+
      geom_vline(xintercept=0.5, color="grey")+
      geom_text(data=subgroup, aes(label=track_name))+
      labs(title= "Scatterplot Songs", x="Valence", y="Loudness")

p + scale_color_brewer(palette = "Pastel1")

Tempo and density albums

# Histogram
ggplot(df, aes(x=tempo))+
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), color="black", fill="purple")+
  geom_density(alpha=0.4, fill="#FF6666")+
  facet_grid(album_name~.)+
  labs(title="Histogram of tempo", x="Tempo(BPM)", y="Density")

Speechiness in relation to valence

# Labeling songs
subgroup <- df |> filter(track_name %in% c("Halfway", "Ghost of You", "Little Bit Louder"))

# Scatter plot with trend
ggplot(df, aes(x=speechiness, y=valence))+
  geom_point(color="blue")+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", alpha=0.1, fill="purple")+
  geom_text(data=subgroup, aes(label=track_name))+
  labs(title= "Scatterplot Songs", x="Speechiness", y="Valence")

Even though it is a weak increase, the higher the speechiness of Mimiâs songs, the more positive!
